Data Modelling – Indexing Concepts ⭐

(Fast Data Retrieval in Databases & Warehouses)

You already learned:

Partitioning → split huge data

Clustering → organize data physically


Now:

Indexing

solves a different problem.

It helps databases find rows quickly without scanning entire tables.


---

First — Why Indexing Exists

Suppose at Amazon:

customers table

customer_id	name	city



Contains:

100 million customers


Now query:

SELECT *
FROM customers
WHERE customer_id = 101;

Without index:

database scans huge table

row-by-row search

very slow


Index solves this.


---

What is an Index?

Theory

An Index is a special data structure that improves the speed of data retrieval operations.

Works similar to:

book index

Instead of reading entire book:

jump directly to page.



---

Simple Definition

Index helps database locate rows faster.


---

Real-Life Analogy ⭐

Without index:

Searching word in book:

read every page


With index:

go directly to page number


Same concept in databases.


---

How Database Works Without Index

Full Table Scan

Database checks every row.

Very expensive for large tables.


---

With Index

Database uses lookup structure:

customer_id -> row location

Much faster retrieval.


---

Most Common Index Type

B-Tree Index ⭐⭐⭐

Default index type in many databases.

Organized like balanced search tree.

Provides:

fast search

fast range queries

efficient lookups



---

Example

Without Index

WHERE customer_id = 101

Scan entire table.


---

With Index

Database directly navigates tree structure.

Huge speed improvement.


---

Primary Key Automatically Indexed ⭐

Very important interview point.

Example:

PRIMARY KEY(customer_id)

Usually creates index automatically.


---

Common Columns to Index ⭐

Column	Why

customer_id	frequent lookup
order_id	transaction search
email	login/search
product_id	joins/filtering



---

Bad Columns for Indexing ⚠️

Low Cardinality Columns

Example:

gender = M/F

Index often useless.

Too few distinct values.


---

Important Concept — Cardinality ⭐

Cardinality = number of unique values.


---

High Cardinality

Good for indexing.

Example:

customer_id

email



---

Low Cardinality

Poor indexing candidates.

Example:

boolean flags

gender



---

Clustered Index vs Non-Clustered Index ⭐

Very common interview topic.


---

Clustered Index

Physically organizes table rows.

Table stored in index order.

Usually:

one clustered index



---

Example

Rows physically sorted by:

customer_id


---

Non-Clustered Index

Separate lookup structure pointing to rows.

Table order unchanged.

Can have:

multiple non-clustered indexes



---

Comparison

Feature	Clustered	Non-Clustered

Physical row order	Yes	No
Count per table	Usually one	Multiple
Speed	Very fast	Fast



---

Composite Index ⭐

Index on multiple columns.

Example:

INDEX(customer_id, order_date)

Useful when queries filter both columns.


---

Example Query

WHERE customer_id = 101
AND order_date = '2026-01-01'

Composite index helps.


---

Important Interview Insight ⭐

Indexes improve read performance but slow down writes.

Very important statement.


---

Why Writes Become Slower

Every:

INSERT

UPDATE

DELETE


must also update indexes.

More indexes:

more maintenance overhead



---

Tradeoff ⭐

Benefit	Cost

Faster reads	Slower writes
Better filtering	Extra storage
Faster joins	Index maintenance



---

Indexing vs Partitioning vs Clustering ⭐⭐⭐

Very common interview comparison.

Feature	Indexing	Partitioning	Clustering

Purpose	Fast row lookup	Split large tables	Organize rows
Best For	Point search	Huge scans	Filter optimization
Example	customer_id lookup	date partitions	customer grouping



---

Real Warehouse Reality ⭐

Traditional OLTP DBs heavily use indexes.

But warehouses like:

Snowflake

Google Cloud BigQuery


often rely more on:

partitioning

clustering

columnar storage


instead of traditional indexing.

Important modern insight.


---

Common Interview Questions

Q1. What is indexing?

Data structure improving retrieval speed.


---

Q2. Why indexes improve performance?

Avoid full table scans.


---

Q3. Why indexes slow writes?

Indexes must also be updated.


---

Q4. Difference between clustered and non-clustered index?

Clustered changes physical row order; non-clustered does not.


---

Q5. Good indexing columns?

High-cardinality frequently searched columns.


